  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "SAORI (\"sa\" meaning self, \"ori\" meaning weave in Japanese) was developed by Misao Jo in Osaka in 1969. The core idea is simple: weaving is a direct expression of the person doing it, and any result is the correct result. There is no draft, no sett, no \"mistake\" worth unpicking. This makes it accessible to anyone who has never touched a loom, and also gives experienced weavers a structured way to weave without structure."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "infoPanel",
        "attrs": {
          "tone": "info",
          "title": "Note on the SAORI name"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "SAORI is a trademarked name for the workshop and certification organisation. This entry describes the method; it is not affiliated with or endorsed by any SAORI studio."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "suppliesCard",
        "attrs": {
          "items": [
            "A simple frame loom (any size; 30 x 40 cm is a good start)",
            "Warp thread: any smooth, strong yarn in a single colour (cotton, linen, or wool)",
            "Weft collection: a mixture of yarns in different weights, textures, and colours; strips of fabric; roving; ribbon; found natural materials",
            "Stick shuttle or fingers for passing the weft",
            "Scissors"
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Setting up the warp"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A frame loom makes "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "warping",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termSlug": "warp"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " straightforward. Wrap the warp yarn around the top and bottom bars of the frame, spacing threads roughly 1 cm apart (or closer or wider; in SAORI this does not need to be precise). Tie off securely. The "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "warp",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termSlug": "warp"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " should have enough tension to hold the "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "shed",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termSlug": "shed"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " open but does not need to be drum-tight."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "orderedList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Step 1: Thread a "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "shed stick",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                        "attrs": {
                          "termSlug": "shed-stick"
                        }
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " through alternate warp ends (over one, under one). When the stick is turned on its side it holds the shed open for the shuttle to pass through."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Step 2: For the return shed (the second half of each plain-weave row), lift the opposite set of warp threads by hand or with a second stick."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Choosing weft materials"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "SAORI "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "weft",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termSlug": "weft"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " can be anything that passes through the "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "shed",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termSlug": "shed"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ": fine singles, chunky wool, strips of cotton jersey cut from old T-shirts, roving bundled loosely, ribbon, paper yarn, dried grasses. Part of the practice is choosing what to weave with, not just how to weave it. Collect materials before you start; lay them out and pick based on what feels right for each row."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Weaving"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "orderedList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Step 1: Pass your first weft through the shed from left to right. Leave a 5 cm tail at the left edge. Do not pull the weft tight. Arc it gently in the shed before beating it down with your fingers so it has enough length to travel over and under the warp without pulling the "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "selvedge",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                        "attrs": {
                          "termSlug": "selvedge"
                        }
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " inward."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Step 2: Change the shed (lift the opposite set of warp ends). Pass the weft from right to left. Beat gently."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Step 3: Continue, changing materials whenever you like. In SAORI, there is no rule about how many rows of one material before switching. End one "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "weft",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                        "attrs": {
                          "termSlug": "weft"
                        }
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " by leaving a 5 cm tail at the edge; start the next with a 5 cm tail overlapping at the same edge. These are woven in or trimmed at the end."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Step 4: Tails can also be left long on purpose as a fringe or woven texture. In SAORI, these choices are aesthetic rather than rule-governed."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Finishing"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "orderedList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Step 1: When the weaving reaches the top of the frame (or when it feels complete), cut the piece off the loom by snipping the warp threads close to the bar."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Step 2: Tie the "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "warp",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                        "attrs": {
                          "termSlug": "warp"
                        }
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " ends together in pairs with an overhand knot to prevent unravelling, or leave as fringe. There is no requirement to hemstitch or fold."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Step 3: Weave in or trim protruding "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "weft",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                        "attrs": {
                          "termSlug": "weft"
                        }
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " tails along the edges using a blunt darning needle, or leave them as part of the finished surface."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "What SAORI is not"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "SAORI is not unstructured in a disorganised sense. Setting up the "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "warp",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termSlug": "warp"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " correctly and passing the "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "weft",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termSlug": "weft"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " through the "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "shed",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termSlug": "shed"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " are real skills. What SAORI removes is the idea that the outcome must match a predetermined pattern or colour plan. The physical mechanics of weaving still apply."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "items": [
            {
              "problem": "The edges are pulling inward and the cloth is getting narrower",
              "solution": "The weft is being pulled too tight at the turn. Arc the weft in a gentle curve inside the shed before beating; this gives it enough length to cover all the warp without squeezing the edges."
            },
            {
              "problem": "The shed is too tight to pass the shuttle through",
              "solution": "The warp threads are too close together or the shed stick is too thin for the warp spacing. Try widening the warp spacing slightly, or use a wider shed stick to hold the opening larger."
            }
          ]
        }
      }
    ]
  }
}
